One ſhould have expected that the queen would have parted in diſguſt with the princeſs, at this rejection of a match, recommended by Philip, and ſo convenient to his purpoſes. But it appears, that the queen was extremely backward in promoting her huſband's deſire of marrying Eliſabeth to the duke of Savoy. On this account, Philip employed Alphonſus, a franciſcan frier, his confeſſor, to confer with her majeſty on the ſubject of this marriage. She told him, that ſhe feared, without conſent of parliament, neither her huſband Philip, nor the nation would be benefited by this alliance. She added, that ſhe could not in point of conſcience preſs this match upon her ſiſter;


meaning perhaps that it would be unjuſt, to force the princeſs to be married, after her reſolute declarations againſt wedlock; or improper and diſhonorable, to match her beneath the dignity of a crowned head. The theological reaſonings of Alphonſus were too refined for the underſtanding, or too weak for the conſcience, of the queen, who ſtill remained inflexible in her former opinion. Upon this, Philip wrote to her in his uſual authoritative ſtyle, adviſing her to examine her own conſcience, and to conſider whether her opinion was founded in truth or in obſtinacy; adding, that if the parliament oppoſed his requeſt, he ſhould lay the blame upon herStrype, Eccl. Mem. iii. 317. ſeq.. The queen, in her anſwer, begged that he would, at leaſt, defer the matter till he returned into England: and that then he might have a better opportunity of judging, what attention her reaſons deſerved. That otherwiſe, ſhe ſhould live in jealouſy of his affections, a ſtate of mind to her worſe than death; but which, to her great diſquietude, ſhe had already began to feel. She obſerved, with many expreſſions of deference to his ſuperior judgment and authority, that, whatever her conſcience might have determined, the matter could not be


poſſibly brought to any ſpeedy concluſion, as the duke would be immediately ordered into the field.



I now return to Thomas Pope, the ſecond ſon of William firſt earl of Downe, uncle to Thomas above-mentioned the ſecond earl, and anceſtor to Francis the preſent lord Guildford. He was born 1598At Wroxton there is a picture, dated 1606, of William Pope, aged 10, and of his brother Thomas, here mentioned, aged 8.. He was knighted by Charles I. at the royal manor of Woodſtock, Aug. 1, 1625MSS. Dugdale, Muſ. Aſhmol. R. fol. 232.. He married at Wroxton, Apr. 20, 1636, Beata, Daughter of Sir Henry Poole of Saperton in Glouceſterſhire, baronetRegiſtr. Wroxton. There is a valuable portrait of this lady at Wroxton, by the ſecond Vanſomer.. He appeared in arms for the royal cauſe. On the death of his nephew Thomas, he became by ſucceſſion, Decemb. 28, 1660, a baronet, and third earl of Downe. He died Jan. 11, 1667, and was buried at Wroxton: as was his counteſs Beata, Jul. 18, 1678Regiſtr. Wroxton.. They had three ſons, Thomas, Henry, and a ſecond Henry; and five daughters, Elenor, Anne, Beata, Frances, and Finetta. Thomas was born, 1640, and on the death of his father, Jan. 11, 1667, became by ſucceſſion a baronet, and fourth


and laſt earl of DowneThere are pictures at Ditchley of the two laſt earls of Downe.. Theſe dignities he enjoyed but a few months; for he died May 18, 1668Regiſtr. Wroxton., and was buried with his anceſtors, in a vault under the chancel at Wroxton. The firſt Henry was born Apr. 11, 1643, and died an infantIbid.. The ſecond Henry was born Jan. 27, 1645Ibid., and died at Oxford in Trinity college, where he was a ſtudent, aged 19, Jun. 20, 1665Ex Tumul. ibid. I find the counteſs of Downe, his mother, making a preſent to the college, "in memoriam filii ſui Dni Henrici Pope hujus collegii comm. defuncti." Regiſtr. ibid. in pergamen. ab ann. 1665, fol. 46. Where ſhe is called, by miſtake, Eliſabetha inſtead of Beata.. Of the daughters, Elenor died an infant 1637Regiſtr. Wroxton.. Anne was born 1637Ibid., and married ſir Edward Boughton, baronet, of Lawford in WarwickſhireMSS. Pedigr. Rawlinſ.. Beata, born 1639, was married Febr. 15, 1668, to William Soames, eſquire, of Thurlowe in SuffolkRegiſtr. Wroxton.. Frances, born 1647, was married March 5, 1671, to ſir Francis North, afterwards lord keeper, and lord North of of GuildfordIbid.; and from this match, grandfather to the preſent Francis lord North and Guildford. She died Nov. 15, 1678Ex Epitaphio., and was buried at Wroxton;


where is an epitaph on her monument, written by Dr. Henry Paman, public orator of the univerſity of Cambridge, who is ſaid to have been well acquainted with her amiable characterNorth's Life of lord keeper North, 4to. p. 84.. The youngeſt daughter, Finetta, was married May 4, 1674, to Robert Hyde, eſquireRegiſtr. Wroxton. See Wood, Ath. Oxon. ii. 543.—f. 235., ſon of Alexander Hyde, biſhop of SaliſburyWhoſe elder brother Laurence Hyde, eſquire, of Heale near Saliſbury, married MARY the daughter of ANTONY WARTON, rector of Bremor in Hamſhire, about the reign of Charles the firſt, and great grandfather to the father of the author of this work. This lady, when a widow, for many days concealed and accommodated in her houſe at Heale, aforeſaid, king Charles the ſecond after his hazardous flight from the battle of Worceſter, in the year 1651, and furniſhed the means for his eſcape into France. At the reſtoration, the king gave her a very valuable picture of himſelf, when a boy, a half-length, painted by Vandyck, and now in the poſſeſſion of my brother doctor Warton of Wincheſter. See Clarendon's HIST. vol. iii. p. 331. edit. fol. 1704.. Thus by the death of male iſſue, and marriage of the female, this family and name, at leaſt in this branch, became extinct ſoon after the reſtoration of Charles the ſecond.
